<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,655,1257]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,655,681]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Comments.</emphasis>
This group was created to group the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Saussure, 1877" authorityName="Saussure" authorityYear="1877" box="[777,1077,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Miogryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[777,900,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Miogryllus</emphasis>
Saussure, 1877
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castaneda, 2011" authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Faguagryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1088,1239,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Faguagryllus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J." pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="55 - 61" refId="ref6393" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. (2011) A new genus of cricket near to Miogryllus and Kazuemba from the Colombian Atlantic coast and the first report of Gryllodes sigillatus from Colombia (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae: Modicogryllini). Zootaxa, 3126 (1), 55 - 61. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3126.1.4" type="journal article" year="2011">Cadena-Castañeda, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority="de Mello, 1990" authorityName="de Mello" authorityYear="1990" box="[260,557,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Kazuemba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[260,378,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Kazuemba</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="de Mello, F." box="[385,557,691,717]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="573 - 575" refId="ref7939" refString="de Mello, F. (1990) A new genus and species of grylline cricket closely related to Miogryllus Saussure, 1877 (Orthoptera, Gryllidae, Gryllinae). Revista brasileira de Entomologia, 34, 573 - 575." type="journal article" year="1990">de Mello, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hebard, 1935" authorityName="Hebard" authorityYear="1935" box="[615,862,691,718]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Gryllita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[615,704,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Gryllita</emphasis>
Hebard, 1935
</taxonomicName>
(this last, senior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Vickery, 1997" authorityName="Vickery" authorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Rubrogryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1190,1337,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Rubrogryllus</emphasis>
Vickery, 1997
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Otte &amp; Perez-Gelabert, 2009" authorityName="Otte &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[259,713,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Geogryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[259,383,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Geogryllus</emphasis>
Otte &amp; Perez-Gelabert, 2009
</taxonomicName>
). The Miogryllae Group is distinguished from the other groups of the subtribe by the male genital characteristics: lateral lophi longer than pseudepiphallic parameres or with similar length, ectophallic fold medially divided, and rami divided on the posterior region (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Garcia Garcia, A." pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="273 - 290" refId="ref6554" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Garcia Garcia, A. (2020) Studies in Colombian Ensifera and adjacent countries: Gigagryllus, a new genus of giant field crickets (Orthoptera: Gryllidae) with comments on current Neotropical field crickets classification. Zootaxa, 4830 (2), 273 - 290. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4830.2.3" type="journal article" year="2020">Cadena-Castañeda &amp; García García 2020</bibRefCitation>
). The wing development and the presence or absence of the tympana are variable. These characters appear and disappear in the different taxa of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laicharting" authorityYear="1781" box="[652,758,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gryllidae</taxonomicName>
and other families, varying even in closely related taxa (
<bibRefCitation author="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J. &amp; Rodriguez, W. A. &amp; Florez, A. P. &amp; Acevedo, A." pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="331 - 356" refId="ref6880" refString="Cadena-Castaneda, O. J., Rodriguez, W. A., Florez, A. P. &amp; Acevedo, A. (2021 c) Studies on Neotropical crickets: The continental Otteiini taxa (Orthoptera: Phalangopsidae), those cave crickets are not confined to the West Indies. Zootaxa, 4981 (2), 331 - 356. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4981.2.7" type="journal article" year="2021">
Cadena-Castañeda 
<emphasis box="[335,385,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">et al</emphasis>
. 2021c
</bibRefCitation>
,d; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov, A. V." box="[503,682,907,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="197 - 209" refId="ref7487" refString="Gorochov, A. V. (2014) Evolution and taxonomic significance of the copulatory apparatus in Ensifera (Orthoptera). Part 1: General concepts and origin. Zoosystematica Rossica, 23 (2), 197 - 209. https: // doi. org / 10.31610 / zsr / 2014.23.2.197" type="journal article" year="2014">Gorochov 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Randell, R." box="[692,845,907,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="1565 - 1607" refId="ref8398" refString="Randell, R. (1964) The male genitalia in Gryllinae (Orthoptera: Gryllidae) and a tribal revision. Canadian Entomologist, 96, 1565 - 1607. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 961565 - 12" type="journal article" year="1964">Randell 1964</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Otte, D. &amp; Alexander, R. D." box="[857,1123,907,933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="1 - 477" refId="ref8229" refString="Otte, D. &amp; Alexander, R. D. (1983) The Australian crickets (Orthoptera: Gryllidae). Monographs of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 22, 1 - 477." type="journal article" year="1983">Otte &amp; Alexander 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,655,1257]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">
The inclusion of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorochov, 2020" authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2020" box="[390,710,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Itarogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[390,523,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Itarogryllus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov, A. V." box="[530,710,943,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" pagination="293 - 297" refId="ref7609" refString="Gorochov, A. V. (2020) New genus and species of the tribe Gryllini (Orthoptera: Gryllidae: Gryllinae) from Peru. Proceedin of the Zoological Institute RAS, 324 (3), 293 - 297. https: // doi. org / 10.31610 / trudyzin / 2020.324.3.293" type="journal article" year="2020">
Gorochov, 
<quantity box="[654,710,943,969]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1308" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" unit="in" value="2020.0">2020</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the Miogryllae Group is questionable. Reviewing the original description, the habitus and size are similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cadena-Castaneda &amp; Tijaro" authorityYear="2020" box="[674,795,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Atsigryllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[674,795,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Atsigryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laicharting" authorityYear="1781" box="[811,905,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Gryllini">Gryllini</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randell" authorityYear="1964" box="[915,1078,979,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Anurogryllina">Anurogryllina</taxonomicName>
), as well as its genital structure. Possibly, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2020" box="[258,391,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Itarogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[258,391,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Itarogryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had a secondary reduction of the medial and lateral lobes; in addition, the ectophallic fold has a feature similar to several 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Randell" authorityYear="1964" box="[463,622,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="420" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Anurogryllina">Anurogryllina</taxonomicName>
species. At the moment, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2020" box="[914,1047,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Itarogryllus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[914,1047,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Itarogryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not included in any subtribe or genus-group, pending further review of the genus status or study of additional material.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,655,1257]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">
<taxonomicName authority="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Tavares &amp; Fernandes, 2022" authorityName="Cadena-Castañeda &amp; Tavares &amp; Fernandes" authorityYear="2022" box="[199,342,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Mellogryllus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[199,342,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Mellogryllus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[348,425,1123,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[348,425,1123,1149]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is allocated in the Miogryllae Group, with a genital feature similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hebard" authorityYear="1935" box="[1194,1283,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Gryllita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[1194,1283,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Gryllita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1289,1320,1123,1150]" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[1289,1315,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">s.l</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but small and silent, being the second silent genus described so far (after 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Mello" authorityYear="1990" box="[853,971,1159,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Gryllidae" genus="Kazuemba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="410" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[853,971,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="410">Kazuemba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). However, both genera are distinguished mainly by the feature of male genitalia. Also, we updated the genera group key, including the new genus described here.
</paragraph>
